<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="05a8f1e030a27ed02eb39d2106de8ec7" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> An Introduction to 'Club Z'<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10198'>George "urthanz" Wilson</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10198&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 17, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Allow me to introduce you to “Club Z” minions and conditions. For those of you in Canada, you’ve probably heard of Zellers (Canadian variation of Wal-Mart). By buying items from Zellers, you receive Club Z points (now HBC Rewards). You can redeem these on items. Now, how does this relate to Lotr? Well, with RotK out and threats as a new game mechanic, it’s the most basic example of what a threat is. Picture threats as points you get for using cards effectively, and twilight as money. You may redeem these points for cool abilities.<br />
<br />
<b>Club Z Conditions</b>:<br />
<br />
0-Sauron’s Hatred<br />
Condition<br />
Shadow: Remove a threat to play a [Mordor] Orc without paying the roaming penalty. <br />
Regroup: Spot a [Mordor] Orc and remove 4 to add a threat.<br />
<br />
This is a basic example of the Club Z point bonuses. Not only does this use Club Z Points to play Orcs for cheaper, but it generates Club Z points by paying $4 apiece.<br />
<br />
Called<br />
Condition<br />
Assignment: Remove 5 threats to assign a Nazgul to a companion. They may discard that companion.<br />
<br />
Another crucial use of threats that can really devastate big fellowships with Cantea.<br />
<br />
Dark Tidings<br />
Condition<br />
Regroup: Spot 2 [Raider] Men and remove 3 to add a threat (limit 1).<br />
<br />
This is a strong card to help Raiders to depend on threats. This is definitely a card to throw in a Raider threat deck.<br />
<br />
Plotting<br />
<br />
Everyone knows what this card does (adding up to 9 threats for one turn). This could do a lot of damage to the opponent if your card expires (see below).<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<b>Club Z Minions</b>:<br />
<br />
Mordor Trooper and Mordor Veteran<br />
Minions-Orcs<br />
Remove 2 threats to make a [Mordor] Orc strength +6/Remove 3 threats to make a [Mordor] Orc strength +8<br />
<br />
This is another way to use up those well-earned points to do something useful.<br />
<br />
Mordor Regular and Mordor Savage<br />
Minions-Orcs<br />
Skirmish: Exert this minion and spot another [Mordor] minion to add a threat.<br />
<br />
Earn some Club Z Points.<br />
<br />
10-Host of Udun<br />
Minion-Orc<br />
21/5/6<br />
Shadow: Remove X threats to make its twilight cost –X.<br />
<br />
Now this is a whopping minion that can really use up those Club Z Points. Sort of like that motorcycle that you earn after saving up for a lot of points.<br />
<br />
9-Army of Udun<br />
Minion-Orc<br />
19/5/6<br />
Shadow: Discard a [Mordor] Orc to add a threat.<br />
Skirmish: Remove a threat to make Army of Udun strength +1.<br />
Regroup: Discard Army of Udun and X other minions to add X threats.<br />
<br />
This is the perfect example of a minion that can generate Club Z points, abuse them, and generate them again at the end of the turn. It is a very efficient way to add threats.<br />
<br />
The Witch-King, Morgul King<br />
Minion-Ringwraith<br />
14/4/3<br />
When you play the Witch-King, you may remove a threat to take a [Nazgul] card into hand from your discard pile. The ring-bearer may not take threat wounds.<br />
<br />
This is a good way to utilize the current Club Z points by taking any Nazgul card from your discard (Nazgul, Event, Condition, Sword, etc.).<br />
<br />
Ulaire Cantea, Faster than Winds<br />
Minion-Ringwraith<br />
10/3/3<br />
When you play Ulaire Cantea, you may add a threat for each companion over 4. <br />
Maneuver: Remove 2 threats and spot another [Nazgul] minion to discard a possession.<br />
<br />
Also a generator and utilizer of Club Z points, this can be very useful against big fellowships, and can devastate Rohan.<br />
<br />
Troop of Haradrim<br />
Minion-Man<br />
10/3/4<br />
Southron. While you can spot 2 threats, this minion is an archer.<br />
While you can spot 3 threats, this minion is fierce.<br />
While you can spot 4 threats, this minion is damage +1.<br />
<br />
This is another efficient way to use Club Z points. Saving them up makes a big group of these minions more powerful.<br />
<br />
Desert Fighter<br />
Minion-Man<br />
8/2/4<br />
Southron. At the start of each skirmish involving this minion, you may remove 1 to add a threat.<br />
<br />
Another way to spend money and receive a threat.<br />
<br />
<b>Card Expires</b>:<br />
<br />
When your Club Z card expires, the points are divided up into wounds, perhaps lowering your minion’s stats, but doing some good damage. This is the main reason for threats in a Bloody Banana deck.<br />
<br />
<b>Sales, Offers, and Locations</b>:<br />
<br />
There are a few sites which take advantage of Threats, by adding threats, or using them to do special abilities. Three big ones come to mind:<br />
<br />
(5)City Gates(6)<br />
When the fellowship moves here, add 3 threats, when the fellowship moves away from here, remove 3 threats.<br />
<br />
Although the offer “expires”, it is good for a certain time, proving to be a good site for the shadow player, especially if they kill a companion at site 5.<br />
<br />
(8)Morgulduin(8)<br />
Shadow: Remove 2 threats to play a Nazgul from your discard pile. Its twilight cost is –2.<br />
<br />
This is a beastly way to swarm with Nazgul, especially by using the above cards to add threats.<br />
<br />
(9)Dagorlad(9)<br />
When the fellowship moves here, add 3 threats.<br />
<br />
This proves to be a deadly site for the fellowship. If one fellowship member dies, at least 3 more wounds are dealt out. <br />
<br />
Hope you enjoyed my article (it may have been dry in some parts, and I apologize). I also hope that you have a better understanding of Threats.<br />
